Objective

We will:

Create a vulnerable PHP application
Install PHPStan
Run PHPStan
Observe findings
Fix findings
Re-run PHPStan
Explain limitations of PHPStan
Compare with Psalm
Step 1: Create a New Folder
mkdir phpstan-training
cd phpstan-training
Step 2: Initialize Composer
composer init

You can simply keep pressing Enter.

Example:

Package name:
whitearrow/phpstan-training

Description:
PHPStan Training Lab

Author:
Hrushikesh

Minimum Stability:
stable

Package Type:
project

License:

Step 3: Install PHPStan
composer require --dev phpstan/phpstan

Verify:

vendor/bin/phpstan --version

Expected:

PHPStan - PHP Static Analysis Tool

Step 4: Create Source Folder
mkdir src

Step 5: Create Vulnerable Code

Create:

nano src/VulnerableApp.php

Paste:

<?php

class VulnerableApp
{
    public function login()
    {
        $username = $_POST['username'];

        if ($admin) {
            echo "Admin Login";
        }

        $user = null;

        echo $user->name;

        return $username + "test";
    }
}

Save.

Step 6: Run PHPStan

Basic scan:

vendor/bin/phpstan analyse src

You should see findings similar to:

Undefined variable: $admin

Cannot access property $name on null

Binary operation "+" between mixed and string
Step 7: Understand Each Finding
Finding 1
if ($admin)

Problem:

$admin

was never defined.

PHPStan:

Undefined variable

Finding 2
$user = null;

echo $user->name;

Problem:

null->name

will crash.

PHPStan catches it.

Finding 3
return $username + "test";

PHP treats:

string + string

incorrectly.

PHPStan warns.

Step 8: Fix the Code

Replace with:

<?php

class VulnerableApp
{
    public function login(bool $admin): string
    {
        $username = $_POST['username'] ?? '';

        if ($admin) {
            echo "Admin Login";
        }

        $user = (object)[
            'name' => 'John'
        ];

        echo $user->name;

        return $username . "test";
    }
}

Notice:

Fixed Undefined Variable
bool $admin
Fixed Null Object
$user = (object)[
    'name' => 'John'
];
Fixed String Concatenation

Wrong:

+

Correct:

.
Step 9: Run Again
vendor/bin/phpstan analyse src

Expected:

[OK] No errors
Step 10: Increase Strictness

Default is relatively forgiving.

Run:

vendor/bin/phpstan analyse src --level=max

This is what I recommend for demonstrations.


Create:
nano src/UserManager.php

Paste:
<?php

class UserManager
{
    public function getUserRole()
    {
        if ($isAdmin) {
            return "Admin";
        }

        return 123;
    }
}


Run:
vendor/bin/phpstan analyse src --level=max

PHPStan will identify:
Undefined variable $isAdmin

and complain about inconsistent return types.

---

Does PHPStan detect SQL Injection?

Example:
$id = $_GET['id'];

$sql =
"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $id";

Run PHPStan.

Result:
No SQL Injection finding

Why?

Because PHPStan is primarily:
Static Analysis not Security SAST Tool.

---

What PHPStan Detects Well

Undefined variables

Null dereference

Wrong return types

Wrong parameter types

Missing methods

Missing properties

Dead code

Type confusion

---

What PHPStan Does NOT Detect Well

❌ SQL Injection

❌ XSS

❌ CSRF

❌ Authentication flaws

❌ Business logic issues

❌ Access control problems

